  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a criminal offense in most countries and is typically covered under criminal legislation. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Legal Classification\n- Money laundering is a serious financial crime\n- It involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Classified as a criminal offense in most jurisdictions\n\n2. Legislative Framework\n- Covered under criminal codes\n- Subject to specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Prosecuted as a criminal activity with potential prison sentences and financial penalties\n\n3. International Perspective\n- Most countries have criminal statutes addressing money laundering\n- International agreements and conventions like the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime support criminal prosecution\n\n4. Typical Consequences\n- Criminal charges\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Substantial financial penalties\n- Asset forfeiture\n\n5. Regulatory Oversight\n- Financial institutions are required to report suspicious transactions\n- Governed by criminal and financial regulatory frameworks\n\nMoney laundering is universally treated as a serious criminal offense with significant legal consequences across different legal systems.",
